<paragraph blockId="6.[151,839,1073,1099]" box="[151,839,1073,1099]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,839,1073,1099]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,839,1073,1099]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
Key to males of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brown" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Walsingham" baseAuthorityYear="2009" box="[397,526,1073,1099]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Episimus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="submicans">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[397,526,1073,1099]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">submicans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group based on genitalia
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="7" type="key">
<keyStep pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1148,1761]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<keyLead pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
1. Setae from basal one-third of valva dramatically asymmetrical from left to right side, with extremely elongate setae on left valva (greater than half the length of valva), and fewer, much shorter setae on right valva (
<figureCitation box="[1237,1361,1183,1206]" captionStart="FIGURES 25–27" captionStartId="38.[151,269,1979,2003]" captionTargetBox="[188,1395,178,1971]" captionTargetId="figure-56@38.[188,1397,134,1999]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURES 25–27. Male genitalia of Megalota; valva spread, phallus removed. 25. M. submicans, image of USNM slide 85,857; 26. M. synchysis, image of USNM slide 84,873; 27. M. peruviana, image of USNM slide 84,891." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5307548" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5307548/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Figs. 25-27</figureCitation>
) ...... 2
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1148,1761]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<keyLead pageId="6" pageNumber="7">- Setae from basal one-third of valva essentially symmetrical from left to right side, with setae less than one-half the length of valva .............................................................................................................................................................. 4</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1148,1761]" box="[151,1435,1287,1310]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<keyLead box="[151,1435,1287,1310]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
2. Basal process of the valva&gt; 3 times as long as wide, narrowed distally (
<figureCitation box="[967,1095,1287,1310]" captionStart="FIGURES 25–27" captionStartId="38.[151,269,1979,2003]" captionTargetBox="[188,1395,178,1971]" captionTargetId="figure-56@38.[188,1397,134,1999]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURES 25–27. Male genitalia of Megalota; valva spread, phallus removed. 25. M. submicans, image of USNM slide 85,857; 26. M. synchysis, image of USNM slide 84,873; 27. M. peruviana, image of USNM slide 84,891." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5307548" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5307548/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Figs. 26, 27</figureCitation>
) ............................................... 3
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1148,1761]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<keyLead pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
- Basal process of the valva &lt;3 times as long as wide, more or less uniformly in width or slightly narrowed subbasally .................................................................................................................................................................... 1. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brown" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Walsingham" baseAuthorityYear="2009" box="[1323,1436,1357,1380]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Episimus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="submicans">
<emphasis box="[1323,1436,1357,1380]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">submicans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1148,1761]" box="[151,1436,1391,1414]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,1391,1414]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
3. Distal end of phallus with flattened flange (
<figureCitation box="[661,740,1391,1414]" captionStart="FIGURES 25–27" captionStartId="38.[151,269,1979,2003]" captionTargetBox="[188,1395,178,1971]" captionTargetId="figure-56@38.[188,1397,134,1999]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURES 25–27. Male genitalia of Megalota; valva spread, phallus removed. 25. M. submicans, image of USNM slide 85,857; 26. M. synchysis, image of USNM slide 84,873; 27. M. peruviana, image of USNM slide 84,891." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5307548" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5307548/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Fig. 27</figureCitation>
), lacking thorns .........................................................3. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brown" authorityYear="2009" box="[1328,1436,1391,1414]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Megalota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="peruviana">
<emphasis box="[1328,1436,1391,1414]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">peruviana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1148,1761]" box="[151,1436,1426,1449]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,1426,1449]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
- Distal end of phallus without flattened flange, with one or two minute thorns (
<figureCitation box="[1031,1109,1426,1449]" captionStart="FIGURES 25–27" captionStartId="38.[151,269,1979,2003]" captionTargetBox="[188,1395,178,1971]" captionTargetId="figure-56@38.[188,1397,134,1999]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURES 25–27. Male genitalia of Megalota; valva spread, phallus removed. 25. M. submicans, image of USNM slide 85,857; 26. M. synchysis, image of USNM slide 84,873; 27. M. peruviana, image of USNM slide 84,891." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5307548" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5307548/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Fig. 26</figureCitation>
) ............................2. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brown" authorityYear="2009" box="[1335,1436,1426,1449]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Megalota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="synchysis">
<emphasis box="[1335,1436,1426,1449]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">synchysis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1148,1761]" box="[151,1436,1460,1484]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,1460,1484]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
4. Uncus with anterior edge straight; posterior edge of tegumen with deep lateral notch (
<figureCitation box="[1112,1190,1460,1483]" captionStart="FIGURES 28–30" captionStartId="39.[151,269,1979,2003]" captionTargetBox="[189,1396,178,1971]" captionTargetId="figure-52@39.[189,1398,138,2003]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="FIGURES 28–30. Male genitalia of Megalota; valva spread, phallus removed. 28. M. aquilonaris, image of USNM slide 124,098; 29. M. vulgaris, image of USNM slide 124,184; 30. M. cacaulana, image of USNM slide 85,871." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5307550" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5307550/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Fig. 30</figureCitation>
).............. 6. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brown" authorityYear="2009" box="[1325,1436,1461,1484]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Megalota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cacaulana">
<emphasis box="[1325,1436,1461,1484]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">cacaulana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1148,1761]" box="[151,1435,1495,1518]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<keyLead box="[151,1435,1495,1518]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">- Uncus with anterior edge rounded; posterior edge of tegumen with shallow lateral notch ......................................... 5</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1148,1761]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<keyLead pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
5. Socius in the form of a conspicuous, rounded, pendant lobe; subbasal patch of setae a dense, compact cluster (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 31–33" captionStartId="40.[151,269,1976,2000]" captionTargetBox="[192,1397,178,1968]" captionTargetId="figure-56@40.[192,1398,138,2000]" captionTargetPageId="40" captionText="FIGURES 31–33. Male genitalia of Megalota; valva spread, phallus removed. 31. M. macrosocia, image of USNM slide 124,139; 32. M. ochreoapex, image of USNM slide 85,863; 33. M. spinulosa, image of USNM slide 84,895." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5307552" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5307552/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Fig. 31</figureCitation>
)............................................................................................................................................................7. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brown" authorityYear="2009" box="[1312,1435,1565,1588]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Megalota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="macrosocia">
<emphasis box="[1312,1435,1565,1588]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">macrosocia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1148,1761]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<keyLead pageId="6" pageNumber="7">- Socii short, membranous, reduced to a patch of fine hairlike bristles; subbasal patch of setae more sparse, not forming a compact cluster..................................................................................................................................................... 6</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1148,1761]" box="[151,1435,1668,1692]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<keyLead box="[151,1435,1668,1692]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
6. Distal setae of incurved process from mid-valva as long as process, projecting ventrally (
<figureCitation box="[1146,1223,1668,1691]" captionStart="FIGURES 28–30" captionStartId="39.[151,269,1979,2003]" captionTargetBox="[189,1396,178,1971]" captionTargetId="figure-52@39.[189,1398,138,2003]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="FIGURES 28–30. Male genitalia of Megalota; valva spread, phallus removed. 28. M. aquilonaris, image of USNM slide 124,098; 29. M. vulgaris, image of USNM slide 124,184; 30. M. cacaulana, image of USNM slide 85,871." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5307550" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5307550/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Fig. 29</figureCitation>
)............. 5. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brown" authorityYear="2009" box="[1348,1435,1669,1692]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Megalota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vulgaris">
<emphasis box="[1348,1435,1669,1692]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">vulgaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1148,1761]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<keyLead pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
- Distal setae of incurved process from mid-valva shorter than process, projecting outward-laterally (
<figureCitation box="[1257,1335,1703,1726]" captionStart="FIGURES 28–30" captionStartId="39.[151,269,1979,2003]" captionTargetBox="[189,1396,178,1971]" captionTargetId="figure-52@39.[189,1398,138,2003]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="FIGURES 28–30. Male genitalia of Megalota; valva spread, phallus removed. 28. M. aquilonaris, image of USNM slide 124,098; 29. M. vulgaris, image of USNM slide 124,184; 30. M. cacaulana, image of USNM slide 85,871." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5307550" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5307550/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Fig. 28</figureCitation>
) ............. ...................................................................................................................................................................4. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brown" authorityYear="2009" box="[1313,1436,1738,1761]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Megalota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aquilonaris">
<emphasis box="[1313,1436,1738,1761]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">aquilonaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
</subSubSection>
